[[Image:Gare_SNCF_Strasbourg_gilets_rouges_13_juin_2014-12.jpg|thumb|Two men wearing gilets at Strasbourg railway station in France]]
A '''gilet''' ({{IPAc-en|dʒ|ɪ|'|l|eɪ}}) is a sleeveless jacket resembling a [[waistcoat]] or [[blouse]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://unabridged.merriam-webster.com/cgi-bin/unabridged?va=gilet|title=Merriam-Webster Unabridged – Gilet entry|publisher=}}</ref> Currently, a gilet is a sleeveless jacket or [[vest]]. They may be waist- to knee-length and are typically straight-sided rather than fitted. However, historically, they were fitted and embroidered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.costumemuseum.jp/french/collection/w_komono/k1.html|title=Sugino Costume Museum|website=www.costumemuseum.jp}}</ref> In a further derivation, in 19th-century dressmaking a gilet was a dress bodice shaped like a man's waistcoat.<ref>Oxford English Dictionary – Gilet entry</ref>

Today, gilets are often worn as an outer layer, for extra warmth outdoors. Fashion gilets may be made of cloth or fake fur, or knitted. Sports gilets are often windproof and/or made of [[Wool|fleece]]. High-end [[hiking]] jackets often have an integral gilet inside them, that can be zipped on and off. [[Racing cyclist]]s use thin light gilets with a windproof front and mesh back. Shooting gilets are rugged and made of leather. Short, overwear gilets are called ''bodywarmers'' in the United Kingdom.

