'''Grecoman''' or '''Graecoman''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: Γραικομάνοι, ''Grekománoi'', [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]: Гъркомани, ''Garkomani'', [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]]: Гркомани, ''Grkomani'', [[Romanian language|Romanian]]: ''Grecomani'', [[Albanian language|Albanian]]: ''Grekomanë'', [[Aromanian language|Aromanian]]: ''Gricumanji'') is a [[pejorative]] term used in [[Bulgaria]], the [[Republic of Macedonia]], [[Romania]] and [[Albania]] to characterize [[Arvanitika|Arvanitic]]-,<ref>{{harvnb|Skendi|1967|p=67}}.</ref> [[Aromanian language|Aromanian]]-,<ref>{{harvnb|Kahl|2002|pp=145–169}}.</ref> and [[Slavic languages|Slavic]]-speaking<ref>{{harvnb|Karakasidou|1997|p=106}}; {{harvnb|Mackridge|Yannakakis|1997|p=148 (Note #11)}}; {{harvnb|Nugent|2002|p=181}}; {{harvnb|Cowan|2000|p=40}}; {{harvnb|Danforth|1997|pp=245–246}}; {{harvnb|Kalyvas|2006|p=312 (Footnote #65)}}; {{harvnb|Rossos|2008|p=145}}; {{harvnb|Brown|2003|p=82}}.</ref> [[Greeks]]. The term generally means "pretending to be a Greek" and implies a non-Greek origin.<ref>{{harvnb|Van Boeschoten|2006|pp=347–377}}.</ref> Another meaning of the term is ''fanatic Greek''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Macedonian Affair - A Historical Review of the Attempts to Create a Counterfeit Nation (Institute of International and Strategic Studies in Athens, Greece)|publisher=Hellenic Resources Network|year=1995–2009|accessdate=12 February 2011|url=http://www.hri.org/docs/affair.html}}</ref> The term is considered highly offensive to the [[Greeks|Greek]] [[people]].<ref name= LMDanforth>{{harvnb|Danforth|1997|p=221}}.</ref> The "Grecoman" is regarded as an ethnic Greek in [[Greece]], but as [[Hellenisation|Hellenized]] minorities in neighboring countries.<ref>{{harvnb|Kontogiorgi|2006|pp=233–234}}.</ref>

