'''Israelization''' ({{lang-he|ישראליזציה}}; Other English spellings: '''Israelification''' or '''Israelisation''') is a term in [[sociology]], study of culture, and [[politics of Israel]] that refers to the processes occurring among minority groups in [[Israel]]. A process in which minority groups adopt, at various levels, the lifestyle, language, culture, political and other characteristics of the dominant group in Israel – [[Sabra (person)|Israeli-born]] [[Hiloni|secular Jews]].
The term is mostly used to describe the changes in the lifestyle and culture of the [[Arab citizens of Israel]] since Israel's creation.<ref>אלחאג', מג'ד, "זהות ואוריינטציה בקרב הערבים בישראל: מצב של פריפריה כפולה", בתוך: ''השסע היהודי ערבי בישראל: מקראה'', בעריכת רות גביזון ודפנה הקר. 2000. עמ' 13-33.</ref> In this context, the term "Palestinization" is used to describe the opposite process – resistance from being overtaken by Israelisation proponents and strengthening political and cultural ties with Palestinians living beyond the [[Green Line (Israel)|Green Line]]. However, sociologist Majid Al-Haj suggests these are not contradictory processes, and that there is an emergence of two parallel identities among Arab citizens of Israel which he called "Politicization".<ref>אלחאג', מג'ד, "זהות ואוריינטציה בקרב הערבים בישראל: מצב של פריפריה כפולה", בתוך: ''השסע היהודי ערבי בישראל: מקראה'', בעריכת רות גביזון ודפנה הקר. 2000. עמ' 13-33.</ref> The equivalent term in Arabic is "Asralah" (أسرلة) derived from the name of "Israel" in Arabic (إسرائيل - Aisraail).
Israelization has been noted amongst the [[Druze in Israel|Druze community in Israel]]. One study noted a trend whereas the post-1950 Druze generation the younger the generation is, the likelier that there is a preference for Hebrew instead of Arabic with many younger Druze using social media having a near absence of Arabic usage amongst other Druze peers.<ref>https://repositories.lib.utexas.edu/handle/2152/ETD-UT-2012-05-5033</ref>
The term "Israelization" is also used occasionally to describe the social and political changes in [[Haredi]] society in Israel, in particular to describe integration into the Israeli political system, their increasing use of the general media in the [[Hebrew]] language, integration into the Israeli labor market etc. In addition, it is sometimes used to describe the assimilation of Jewish immigrants to Israel ([[Aliyah]]) among the native-born Israelis and amongst the veterans Jewish immigrants.
