'''Kohlrosing''' (a.k.a. Kolrosing) is the Scandinavian tradition of incising thin decorative lines and patterns in carved wood and filling with dark powders (charcoal, coal dust, coffee grounds, graphite, ground bark) or colored wax, etc. for contrast,.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://pinewoodforge.com/basics-of-kolrosing/ | title=Basics of Kohlrosing | last1=Ritger | first1=Judy | last2=Stubbs | first2=Del}}</ref> Kohlrosing dates back to at least [[Viking]] times.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=nN9TCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=Kohlrosing&source=bl&ots=D4B7EZUTW-&sig=b2CjIk7v5OEBdRpsmeMyGH6C5gU&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiu5sqdyKLaAhUrslQKHdoNBhY4ChDoAQgnMAA#v=onepage&q=Kohlrosing&f=false|title=The Artful Wooden Spoon: How to Make Exquisite Keepsakes for the Kitchen|first=Joshua|last=Vogel|date=10 November 2015|publisher=Chronicle Books|accessdate=23 April 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trollhaugenalberta.ca/courses.htm|title=Trollhaugen Language Arts & Culture Camp|first=Cindy|last=Cunningham|website=www.trollhaugenalberta.ca|accessdate=23 April 2018}}</ref>
Notable contemporary exponents include Judy Ritger (USA), [[Wille Sundqvist]] (Sweden)<ref>{{cite | title=Talja med kniv och yxa | first=Wille | last=Sunqvist | date=1988 |publisher=Verfasser und LTs}}</ref><ref>{{cite | title=Swedish Carving Techniques | first=Wille | last=Sunqvist | date=1990 |publisher= Taunton Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite | title=Swedische Schnitz-Schule, Arbeiten mit messer und axt | first=Wille | last=Sunqvist | date=2004 |publisher=Verlag Th. Schafer}}</ref> and [[Jogge Sundqvist]] (Sweden)<ref>{{cite | title=Carving Swedish Woodenware | first=Jogge | last=Sunqvist | date=2014 |publisher=Taunton DVD}}</ref><ref>{{cite | title=Slojda I tra | first=Jogge | last=Sunqvist | date=2016 |publisher=Lost Art Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite | title=Slojd in Wood | first=Jogge | last=Sunqvist | date=2018 |publisher=Lost Art Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.surolle.se/en/ |first=Jogge | last=Sunqvist | title=surolle | website=www.surolle.se }}</ref>
