{{short description|20th century Ashanti carving sculptor}} {{refimprove|date=November 2018}}
{{lead too short|date=November 2018}} {{Infobox artist | name = Osei Bonsu | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 22 October 1900 | birth_place = [[Kumase]], [[Ashanti Region]], [[Ghana]] | death_date = 1 March 1977 | death_place = [[Kumase]], [[Ashanti Region]], [[Ghana]] | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | nationality = | movement = [[Ashanti carving]] | training = | field = Sculpture | works = }}
'''Osei Bonsu''' (October 22, 1900 - March 1, 1977) was a famed sculptor of [[Ashanti carving]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Ross|first=Doran|date=February 1984|title=The Art of Osei Bonsu|url=https://exchange.umma.umich.edu/system/local_files/files/000/000/188/original/Ross__The_Art_of_Osei_Bonsu.pdf?1490367965|journal=African Arts|volume=Vol. 17, No. 2|pages=28–90|via=}}</ref>
==Life and career==
Bonsu was taught carving as an apprentice under his father. He got his start via commissions from [[Akan people|Akan]] chiefs. He carved prolifically from his early twenties to his death in 1977. He was the chief carver of three [[Asantehene]] (absolute monarchs of the [[Kingdom of Ashanti]]): [[Prempeh I]], [[Osei Tutu Agyeman Prempeh II]], and [[Opoku Ware II]]. In this role he gained many commissions, including work for the [[Ghana National Museum]].<ref name=":0" />
In 1975 and 1976, Bonsu toured the United States as part of the [[Smithsonian Institution]]'s Festival of American Folklore.<ref name=":0" />
==Works and style==
After Prempeh I's return from exile, Bonsu was commissioned to various regalia including linguist staffs, sword hilts, flywhisk sandals, and ornaments for sandals. Importantly, he was also asked to help in reconstructing the [[Golden Stool]], the famous symbol of power for Ashanti monarchs.<ref name=":0" />
His work is on display in the [[British Museum]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=629257&partId=1&searchText=Meyerowitz&page=1|title=umbrella / terminal|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref> the Ghana National Museum, and the [[Fowler Museum at UCLA]].<ref name=":0" />
